15 //*************************************************************************
16 // V3Tristate's Transformations:
17 //
18 // Modify the design to expand tristate logic into its
19 // corresponding two state representation. At the lowest levels,
20 //
21 // In detail:
22 //
23 // Over each module, from child to parent:
24 // Build a graph, connecting signals together so we can propagate tristates
25 // Variable becomes tristate with
26 // VAR->isInout
27 // VAR->isPullup/isPulldown (converted to AstPullup/AstPulldown
28 // BufIf0/1
29 // All variables on the LHS need to become tristate when there is:
30 // CONST-> with Z value on the RHS of an assignment
31 // AstPin with lower connection a tristate
32 // A tristate signal on the RHS
33 // (this can't generally be determined until that signal is resolved)
34 // When LHS becomes tristate, then mark all RHS nodes as tristate
35 // so any tristate varrefs on the right will propagate.
36 //
37 // Walk graph's tristate indication on each logic block with tristates
38 // propagating downstream to every other logic block.
39 //
40 // Expressions that have Z in them are converted into two state
41 // drivers and corresponding output enable signals are generated.
42 // These enable signals get transformed and regenerated through any
43 // logic that they may go through until they hit the module level. At
44 // the module level, all the output enable signals from what can be
45 // many tristate drivers are combined together to produce a single
46 // driver and output enable. If the signal propagates up into higher
47 // modules, then new ports are created with for the signal with
48 // suffixes __en and __out. The original port is turned from an inout
49 // to an input and the __out port carries the output driver signal and
50 // the __en port carried the output enable for that driver.
51 //
52 // Note 1800-2012 adds user defined resolution functions. This suggests
53 // long term this code should be scoped-based and resolve all nodes at once
54 // rather than hierarchically. If/when that is done, make sure to avoid
55 // duplicating vars and logic that is common between each instance of a
56 // module.
57 //
58 //
59 // Another thing done in this phase is signal strength handling.
60 // Currently they are only supported in assignments and gates parsed as assignments (see verilog.y)
61 // when any of the cases occurs:
62 // - it is possible to statically resolve all drivers,
63 // - all assignments that passed the static resolution have symmetric strengths (the same strength
64 // is related to both 0 and 1 values).
65 //
66 // It is possible to statically resolve all drivers when the strongest assignment has RHS marked as
67 // non-tristate. If the RHS is equal to z, that assignment has to be skipped. Since the value may
68 // be not known at Verilation time, cases with tristates on RHS can't be handled statically.
69 //
70 // Static resolution is split into 2 parts.
71 // First part can be done before tristate propagation. It is about removing assignments that are
72 // weaker or equally strong as the strongest assignment with constant on RHS that has all bits
73 // the same (equal to 0 or 1). It is done in the following way:
74 // - The assignment of value 0 (size may be greater than 1), that has greatest strength (the
75 // one corresponding to 0) of all other assignments of 0, has to be found.
76 // - The same is done for value '1 and strength corresponding to value 1.
77 // - The greater of these two strengths is chosen. If they are equal the one that corresponds
78 // to 1 is taken as the greatest.
79 // - All assignments, that have strengths weaker or equal to the one that was found before, are
80 // removed. They are the assignments with constants on the RHS and also all assignments that have
81 // both strengths non-greater that the one was found, because they are weaker no matter what is on
82 // RHS.
83 //
84 // Second part of static resolution is done after tristate propagation.
85 // At that moment it is known that some expressions can't be equal to z. The exact value is
86 // unknown (except the ones with constants that were handled before), so weaker of both strengths
87 // has to be taken into account. All weaker assignments can be safely removed. It is done in
88 // similar way to the first part:
89 // - The assignment with non-tristate RHS with the greatest weaker strength has to be found.
90 // - Then all not stronger assignments can be removed.
91 //
92 // All assignments that are stronger than the strongest with non-tristate RHS are then tried to be
93 // handled dynamically. Currently it is supported only on assignments with symmetric strengths.
94 // In this case, the exact value of the RHS doesn't matter. It only matters if it equals z or not.
95 // Such assignments are handled by changing the values to z of these bits that are overwritten by
96 // stronger assignments. Then all assignments can be aggregated as they would have equal strengths
97 // (by | on them and their __en expressions). To change the value to z, the RHS should be & with
98 // negation of __en expression of stronger assignments. Changing RHS's __en expression is not
99 // needed, because it will be then aggregated with __en expression of stronger assignments using |,
100 // so & with the negation can be safely skipped.
101 // So the values of overwritten bits are actually changed to 0, which doesn't affect stronger
102 // assignments, because | operation was used.
103 //
104 // Dynamic handling is implemented in the following way:
105 // - group the assignments by their strengths,
106 // - handle assignments of the same strength by aggregating values with |
107 // - assign results to var__strength and var__strength__en variables
108 // - aggregate the results:
109 // orp = orp | (var__strength & ~enp)
110 // enp = enp | var__strength__en,
111 // where orp is aggregated value and enp is aggregated __en value.
112 //
113 // There is a possible problem with equally strong assignments, because multiple assignments with
114 // the same strength, but different values should result in x value, but these values are
115 // unsupported.
116 //*************************************************************************
